# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-forensics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Although it is most often associated with the investigation of a wide variety of computer crime, computer forensics may also be used in civil proceedings.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] The discipline involves similar techniques and principles to data recovery, but with additional guidelines and practices designed to create a legal audit trail.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Evidence from computer forensics investigations is usually subjected to the same guidelines and practices as other digital evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] It has been used in a number of high-profile cases and is accepted as reliable within U.S. and European court systems.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] In the early 1980s, personal computers became more accessible to consumers, leading to their increased use in criminal activity (for example, to help commit fraud).
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] At the same time, several new "computer crimes" were recognized (such as cracking).
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] The discipline of computer forensics emerged during this time as a method to recover and investigate digital evidence for use in court.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Since then, computer crime and computer-related crime has grown, with the FBI reporting a suspected 791,790 internet crimes in 2020, a 69% increase over the amount reported in 2019.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Today, computer forensics is used to investigate a wide variety of crimes, including child pornography, fraud, espionage, cyberstalking, murder, and rape.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] The discipline also features in civil proceedings as a form of information gathering (e.g., Electronic discovery).
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Forensic techniques and expert knowledge are used to explain the current state of a *digital artifact*, such as a computer system, storage medium (e.g., hard disk or CD-ROM), or an electronic document (e.g., an email message or JPEG image).
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] The scope of a forensic analysis can vary from simple information retrieval to reconstructing a series of events.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] In a 2002 book, *Computer Forensics*, authors Kruse and Heiser define computer forensics as involving "the preservation, identification, extraction, documentation and interpretation of computer data".
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] They describe the discipline as "more of an art than a science," indicating that forensic methodology is backed by flexibility and extensive domain knowledge.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] However, while several methods can be used to extract evidence from a given computer, the strategies used by law enforcement are fairly rigid and lack the flexibility found in the civilian world.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Computer forensics is often confused with cybersecurity.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Cybersecurity focuses on prevention and protection, while computer forensics is more reactionary and active, involving activities such as tracking and exposing.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] System security usually encompasses two teams: cybersecurity and computer forensics, which work together.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] A cybersecurity team creates systems and programs to protect data; if these fail, the computer forensics team recovers the data and investigates the intrusion and theft.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Both areas require knowledge of computer science.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Computer forensics are used to convict those involved in physical and digital crimes.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Some of these computer-related crimes include interruption, interception, copyright infringement, and fabrication.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] *Interruption* relates to the destruction and stealing of computer parts and digital files.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] *Interception* is the unauthorized access of files and information stored on technological devices.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Copyright infringement refers to using, reproducing, and distributing copyrighted information, including software piracy.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] *Fabrication* involves accusing someone of using false data and information inserted into the system through an unauthorized source.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Examples of interceptions include the Bank NSP case, Sony.Sambandh.com case, and business email compromise scams.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] In court, computer forensic evidence is subject to the usual requirements for digital evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] This requires that information be authentic, reliably obtained, and admissible.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Different countries have specific guidelines and practices for evidence recovery.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] In the United Kingdom, examiners often follow Association of Chief Police Officers guidelines that help ensure the authenticity and integrity of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] While voluntary, the guidelines are widely accepted in British courts.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Computer forensics has been used as evidence in criminal law since the mid-1980s.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Computer forensic investigations typically follow the standard digital forensic process, consisting of four phases: acquisition, examination, analysis, and reporting.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Investigations are usually performed on static data (i.e., acquired images) rather than "live" systems.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] This differs from early forensic practices, when a lack of specialized tools often required investigators to work on live data.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] The computer forensics lab is a secure environment where electronic data can be preserved, managed, and accessed under controlled conditions, minimizing the risk of damage or alteration to the evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Forensic examiners are provided with the resources necessary to extract meaningful data from the devices they examine.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] where encryption keys can be retrieved, or for imaging the logical hard drive volume (a live acquisition) before shutting down the computer.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Live analysis is also beneficial when examining networked systems or cloud-based devices that cannot be accessed physically.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] A common forensic technique involves recovering deleted files.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Forensic software can "carve" files by searching for known file headers and reconstructing deleted data.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Steganography involves concealing data within another file, such as hiding illegal content within an image.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Forensic investigators detect steganography by comparing file hashes, as any hidden data will alter the hash value of the file.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Phone companies typically retain logs of received calls, which can help create timelines and establish suspects' locations at the time of a crime.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] are useful in narrowing down suspects based on their connections to the victim.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Text messages contain timestamps and remain in company servers, often indefinitely, even if deleted from the device.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] These records are valuable evidence for reconstructing communication between individuals.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Photos can provide critical evidence, supporting or disproving alibis by showing the location and time they were taken.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Some victims may have recorded pivotal moments, capturing details like the attacker's voice, which could provide crucial evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Volatile data is stored in memory or in transit and is lost when the computer is powered down.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] It resides in locations such as registries, cache, and RAM.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] When seizing evidence, if a machine is still active, volatile data stored solely in RAM may be lost if not recovered before shutting down the system.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] "Live analysis" can be used to recover RAM data (e.g., using Microsoft's COFEE tool, WinDD, WindowsSCOPE) before removing the machine.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Tools like CaptureGUARD Gateway allow for the acquisition of physical memory from a locked computer.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] RAM data can sometimes be recovered after power loss, as the electrical charge in memory cells dissipates slowly.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Techniques like the cold boot attack exploit this property.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Lower temperatures and higher voltages increase the chance of recovery, but it is often impractical to implement these techniques in field investigations.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Tools that extract volatile data often require the computer to be in a forensic lab to maintain the chain of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] In some cases, a live desktop can be transported using tools like a mouse jiggler to prevent sleep mode and an uninterruptible power supply (UPS) to maintain power.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Page files from file systems with journaling features, such as NTFS and ReiserFS, can also be reassembled to recover RAM data stored during system operation.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Numerous open-source and commercial tools exist for computer forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Common forensic analysis includes manual reviews of media, Windows registry analysis, password cracking, keyword searches, and the extraction of emails and images.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Tools such as Autopsy (software), Belkasoft Evidence Center X, Forensic Toolkit (FTK), and EnCase are widely used in digital forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] A digital forensics analyst is responsible for preserving digital evidence, cataloging collected evidence, analyzing evidence relevant to the ongoing case, responding to cyber breaches (often in a corporate context), writing reports containing findings, and testifying in court.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] A digital forensic analyst may also be referred to as a computer forensic analyst, digital forensic examiner, cyber forensic analyst, forensic technician, or other similarly named titles, though these roles perform similar duties.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Several computer forensics certifications are available, such as the ISFCE Certified Computer Examiner, Digital Forensics Investigation Professional (DFIP), and IACRB Certified Computer Forensics Examiner.
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] The top vendor-independent certification, particularly within the EU, is the Certified Cyber Forensics Professional (CCFP).
[src:digital-forensics/computer-forensics] Many commercial forensic software companies also offer proprietary certifications.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In computing, **data recovery** is a process of retrieving deleted, inaccessible, lost, corrupted, damaged, or overwritten data from secondary storage, removable media or files, when the data stored in them cannot be accessed in a usual way.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The data is most often salvaged from storage media such as internal or external hard disk drives (HDDs), solid-state drives (SSDs), USB flash drives, magnetic tapes, CDs, DVDs, RAID subsystems, and other electronic devices.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Recovery may be required due to physical damage to the storage devices or logical damage to the file system that prevents it from being mounted by the host operating system (OS).
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Logical failures occur when the hard drive devices are functional but the user or automated-OS cannot retrieve or access data stored on them.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Logical failures can occur due to corruption of the engineering chip, lost partitions, firmware failure, or failures during formatting/re-installation.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Data recovery can be a very simple or technical challenge.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] This is why there are specific software companies specialized in this field that help to get back data on your system.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The most common data recovery scenarios involve an operating system failure, malfunction of a storage device, logical failure of storage devices, accidental damage or deletion, etc.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] (typically, on a single-drive, single-partition, single-OS system), in which case the ultimate goal is simply to copy all important files from the damaged media to another new drive.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] This can be accomplished using a Live CD, or DVD by booting directly from a ROM or a USB drive instead of the corrupted drive in question.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Many Live CDs or DVDs provide a means to mount the system drive and backup drives or removable media, and to move the files from the system drive to the backup media with a file manager or optical disc authoring software.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Such cases can often be mitigated by disk partitioning and consistently storing valuable data files (or copies of them) on a different partition from the replaceable OS system files.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Another scenario involves a drive-level failure, such as a compromised file system or drive partition, or a hard disk drive failure.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In any of these cases, the data is not easily read from the media devices.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] If a drive recovery is necessary, the drive itself has typically failed permanently, and the focus is rather on a one-time recovery, salvaging whatever data can be read.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In a third scenario, files have been accidentally "deleted" from a storage medium by the users.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Typically, the contents of deleted files are not removed immediately from the physical drive; instead, references to them in the directory structure are removed, and thereafter space the deleted data occupy is made available for later data overwriting.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In the mind of end users, deleted files cannot be discoverable through a standard file manager, but the deleted data still technically exists on the physical drive.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In the meantime, the original file contents remain, often several disconnected fragments, and may be recoverable if not overwritten by other data files.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The term "data recovery" is also used in the context of forensic applications or espionage, where data which have been encrypted, hidden, or deleted, rather than damaged, are recovered.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Sometimes data present in the computer gets encrypted or hidden due to reasons like virus attacks which can only be recovered by some computer forensic experts.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] A wide variety of failures can cause physical damage to storage media, which may result from human errors and natural disasters.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] CD-ROMs can have their metallic substrate or dye layer scratched off; hard disks can suffer from a multitude of mechanical failures, such as head crashes, PCB failure, and failed motors; tapes can simply break.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Physical damage to a hard drive, even in cases where a head crash has occurred, does not necessarily mean permanent data loss.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] However, in extreme cases, such as prolonged exposure to moisture and corrosion —like the lost Bitcoin hard drive of James Howells, buried in the Newport landfill for over a decade — recovery is usually impossible.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In rare cases, forensic techniques such as magnetic force microscopy (MFM) have been explored to detect residual magnetic traces when data holds exceptional value.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Other techniques employed by many professional data recovery companies can typically salvage most, if not all, of the data that had been lost when the failure occurred.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Of course, there are exceptions to this, such as cases where severe damage to the hard drive platters may have occurred.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] However, if the hard drive can be repaired and a full image or clone created, then the logical file structure can be rebuilt in most instances.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Most physical damage cannot be repaired by end users.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] For example, opening a hard disk drive in a normal environment can allow airborne dust to settle on the platter and become caught between the platter and the read/write head.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] During normal operation, read/write heads float 3 to 6 nanometers above the platter surface, and the average dust particles found in a normal environment are typically around 30,000 nanometers in diameter.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] When these dust particles get caught between the read/write heads and the platter, they can cause new head crashes that further damage the platter and thus compromise the recovery process.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Furthermore, end users generally do not have the hardware or technical expertise required to make these repairs.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Consequently, data recovery companies are often employed to salvage important data with the more reputable ones using class 100 dust- and static-free cleanrooms.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Recovering data from physically damaged hardware can involve multiple techniques.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Some damage can be repaired by replacing parts in the hard disk.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] This alone may make the disk usable, but there may still be logical damage.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] A specialized disk-imaging procedure is used to recover every readable bit from the surface.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Once this image is acquired and saved on a reliable medium, the image can be safely analyzed for logical damage and will possibly allow much of the original file system to be reconstructed.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] A common misconception is that a damaged printed circuit board (PCB) may be simply replaced during recovery procedures by an identical PCB from a healthy drive.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] While this may work in rare circumstances on hard disk drives manufactured before 2003, it will not work on newer drives.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Electronics boards of modern drives usually contain drive-specific adaptation data (generally a map of bad sectors and tuning parameters) and other information required to properly access data on the drive.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Replacement boards often need this information to effectively recover all of the data.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The replacement board may need to be reprogrammed.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Some manufacturers (Seagate, for example) store this information on a serial EEPROM chip, which can be removed and transferred to the replacement board.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Each hard disk drive has what is called a *system area* or *service area*; this portion of the drive, which is not directly accessible to the end user, usually contains drive's firmware and adaptive data that helps the drive operate within normal parameters.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] One function of the system area is to log defective sectors within the drive; essentially telling the drive where it can and cannot write data.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The sector lists are also stored on various chips attached to the PCB, and they are unique to each hard disk drive.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] If the data on the PCB do not match what is stored on the platter, then the drive will not calibrate properly.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In most cases the drive heads will click because they are unable to find the data matching what is stored on the PCB.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The term "logical damage" refers to situations in which the error is not a problem in the hardware and requires software-level solutions.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In some cases, data on a hard disk drive can be unreadable due to damage to the partition table or file system, or to (intermittent) media errors.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] This type of data recovery can be performed by people without expertise in drive hardware as it requires no special physical equipment or access to platters.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Sometimes data can be recovered using relatively simple methods and tools; more serious cases can require expert intervention, particularly if parts of files are irrecoverable.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Data carving is the recovery of parts of damaged files using knowledge of their structure.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] After data has been physically overwritten on a hard disk drive, it is generally assumed that the previous data are no longer possible to recover.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In 1996, Peter Gutmann, a computer scientist, presented a paper that suggested overwritten data could be recovered through the use of magnetic force microscopy.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In 2001, he presented another paper on a similar topic.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] To guard against this type of data recovery, Gutmann and Colin Plumb designed a method of irreversibly scrubbing data, known as the Gutmann method and used by several disk-scrubbing software packages.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Substantial criticism has followed, primarily dealing with the lack of any concrete examples of significant amounts of overwritten data being recovered.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Gutmann's article contains a number of errors and inaccuracies, particularly regarding information about how data is encoded and processed on hard drives.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Although Gutmann's theory may be correct, there is no practical evidence that overwritten data can be recovered, while research has shown to support that overwritten data cannot be recovered.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Solid-state drives (SSD) overwrite data differently from hard disk drives (HDD) which makes at least some of their data easier to recover.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Most SSDs use flash memory to store data in pages and blocks, referenced by logical block addresses (LBA) which are managed by the flash translation layer (FTL).
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] When the FTL modifies a sector it writes the new data to another location and updates the map so the new data appear at the target LBA.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] This leaves the pre-modification data in place, with possibly many generations, and recoverable by data recovery software.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Sometimes, data present in the physical drives (Internal/External Hard disk, Pen Drive, etc.) gets lost, deleted and formatted due to circumstances like virus attack, accidental deletion or accidental use of SHIFT+DELETE.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In these cases, data recovery software is used to recover/restore the data files.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] In the list of logical failures of hard disks, a logical bad sector is the most common fault leading data not to be readable.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Sometimes it is possible to sidestep error detection even in software, and perhaps with repeated reading and statistical analysis recover at least some of the underlying stored data.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Sometimes prior knowledge of the data stored and the error detection and correction codes can be used to recover even erroneous data.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] However, if the underlying physical drive is degraded badly enough, at least the hardware surrounding the data must be replaced, or it might even be necessary to apply laboratory techniques to the physical recording medium.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Each of the approaches is progressively more expensive, and as such progressively more rarely sought.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Eventually, if the final, physical storage medium has indeed been disturbed badly enough, recovery will not be possible using any means; the information has irreversibly been lost.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Recovery experts do not always need to have physical access to the damaged hardware.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] When the lost data can be recovered by software techniques, they can often perform the recovery using remote access software over the Internet, LAN or other connection to the physical location of the damaged media.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The process is essentially no different from what the end user could perform by themselves.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Remote recovery requires a stable connection with an adequate bandwidth.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] However, it is not applicable where access to the hardware is required, as in cases of physical damage.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Usually, there are four phases when it comes to successful data recovery, though that can vary depending on the type of data corruption and recovery required.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The hard drive is repaired in order to get it running in some form, or at least in a state suitable for reading the data from it.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] For example, if heads are bad they need to be changed; if the PCB is faulty then it needs to be fixed or replaced; if the spindle motor is bad the platters and heads should be moved to a new drive.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] When a hard disk drive fails, the importance of getting the data off the drive is the top priority.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The longer a faulty drive is used, the more likely further data loss is to occur.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Creating an image of the drive will ensure that there is a secondary copy of the data on another device, on which it is safe to perform testing and recovery procedures without harming the source.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] After the drive has been cloned to a new drive, it is suitable to attempt the retrieval of lost data.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] If the drive has failed logically, there are a number of reasons for that.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] (MBR) in order to read the file system's data structure and retrieve stored data.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Data damage can be caused when, for example, a file is written to a sector on the drive that has been damaged.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] This is the most common cause in a failing drive, meaning that data needs to be reconstructed to become readable.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Corrupted documents can be recovered by several software methods or by manually reconstructing the document using a hex editor.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The Windows operating system can be reinstalled on a computer that is already licensed for it.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] The reinstallation can be done by downloading the operating system or by using a "restore disk" provided by the computer manufacturer.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Eric Lundgren was fined and sentenced to U.S. federal prison in April 2018 for producing 28,000 restore disks and intending to distribute them for about 25 cents each as a convenience to computer repair shops.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] Data recovery cannot always be done on a running system.
[src:digital-forensics/data-recovery] As a result, a boot disk, live CD, live USB, or any other type of live distro contains a minimal operating system.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Digital forensics investigations have a variety of applications.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The most common is to support or refute a hypothesis before criminal or civil courts.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Criminal cases involve the alleged breaking of laws that are defined by legislation and enforced by the police and prosecuted by the state, such as murder, theft, and assault against the person.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Forensics may also feature in the private sector, such as during internal corporate investigations or intrusion investigations (a special probe into the nature and extent of an unauthorized network intrusion).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The technical aspect of an investigation is divided into several sub-branches related to the type of digital devices involved: computer forensics, network forensics, forensic data analysis, and mobile device forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The typical forensic process encompasses the seizure, forensic imaging (acquisition), and analysis of digital media, followed with the production of a report of the collected evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] As well as identifying direct evidence of a crime, digital forensics can be used to attribute evidence to specific suspects, confirm alibis or statements, determine intent, identify sources (for example, in copyright cases), or authenticate documents.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Investigations are much broader in scope than other areas of forensic analysis (where the usual aim is to provide answers to a series of simpler questions), often involving complex time-lines or hypotheses.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Prior to the 1970s, crimes involving computers were dealt with using existing laws.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The first computer crimes were recognized in the 1978 Florida Computer Crimes Act, which included legislation against the unauthorized modification or deletion of data on a computer system.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Over the next few years, the range of computer crimes being committed increased, and laws were passed to deal with issues of copyright, privacy/harassment (e.g., cyber bullying, happy slapping, cyber stalking, and online predators), and child pornography.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] It was not until the 1980s that federal laws began to incorporate computer offences.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Canada was the first country to pass legislation in 1983.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This was followed by the US Federal *Computer Fraud and Abuse Act* in 1986, Australian amendments to their crimes acts in 1989, and the British *Computer Misuse Act* in 1990.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Digital forensics methods are increasingly being applied to preserve and authenticate born-digital cultural materials in heritage institutions.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The growth in computer crime during the 1980s and 1990s caused law enforcement agencies to begin establishing specialized groups, usually at the national level, to handle the technical aspects of investigations.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] For example, in 1984, the FBI launched a *Computer Analysis and Response Team* and the following year a computer crime department was set up within the British Metropolitan Police fraud squad.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] As well as being law enforcement professionals, many of the early members of these groups were also computer hobbyists and became responsible for the field's initial research and direction.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] One of the first practical (or at least publicized) examples of digital forensics was Cliff Stoll's pursuit of hacker Markus Hess in 1986.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Stoll, whose investigation made use of computer and network forensic techniques, was not a specialized examiner.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Many of the earliest forensic examinations followed the same profile.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Throughout the 1990s, there was high demand for these new, and basic, investigative resources.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The strain on central units lead to the creation of regional, and even local, level groups to help handle the load.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] For example, the British National Hi-Tech Crime Unit was set up in 2001 to provide a national infrastructure for computer crime, with personnel located both centrally in London and with the various regional police forces (the unit was folded into the Serious Organised Crime Agency (SOCA) in 2006).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] During this period, the science of digital forensics grew from the ad-hoc tools and techniques developed by these hobbyist practitioners.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This is in contrast to other forensics disciplines, which developed from work by the scientific community.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] It was not until 1992 that the term "computer forensics" was used in academic literature (although prior to this, it had been in informal use); a paper by Collier and Spaul attempted to justify this new discipline to the forensic science world.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This swift development resulted in a lack of standardization and training.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In his 1995 book, *High-Technology Crime: Investigating Cases Involving Computers*, K.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Since 2000, in response to the need for standardization, various bodies and agencies have published guidelines for digital forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The Scientific Working Group on Digital Evidence (SWGDE) produced a 2002 paper, *Best practices for Computer Forensics*, this was followed, in 2005, by the publication of an ISO standard (ISO 17025, *General requirements for the competence of testing and calibration laboratories*).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] A European-led international treaty, the Budapest Convention on Cybercrime, came into force in 2004 with the aim of reconciling national computer crime laws, investigative techniques, and international co-operation.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The treaty has been signed by 43 nations (including the US, Canada, Japan, South Africa, UK, and other European nations) and ratified by 16.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The issue of training also received attention.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Commercial companies (often forensic software developers) began to offer certification programs, and digital forensic analysis was included as a topic at the UK specialist investigator training facility, Centrex.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In the late 1990s, mobile devices became more widely available, advancing beyond simple communication devices, and were found to be rich forms of information, even for crime not traditionally associated with digital forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Despite this, digital analysis of phones has lagged behind traditional computer media, largely due to problems over the proprietary nature of devices.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Focus has also shifted onto internet crime, particularly the risk of cyber warfare and cyberterrorism.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The field of digital forensics still faces unresolved issues.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] A 2009 paper, "Digital Forensic Research: The Good, the Bad and the Unaddressed" by Peterson and Shenoi, identified a bias towards Windows operating systems in digital forensics research.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The paper also identified continued training issues, as well as the prohibitively high cost of entering the field.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] During the 1980s, very few specialized digital forensic tools existed.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Consequently, investigators often performed live analysis on media, examining computers from within the operating system using existing sysadmin tools to extract evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This practice carried the risk of modifying data on the disk, either inadvertently or otherwise, which led to claims of evidence tampering.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] A number of tools were created during the early 1990s to address the problem.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The need for such software was first recognized in 1989 at the Federal Law Enforcement Training Center, resulting in the creation of IMDUMP (by Michael White) and in 1990, SafeBack (developed by Sydex).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Similar software was developed in other countries; DIBS (a hardware and software solution) was released commercially in the UK in 1991, and Rob McKemmish released *Fixed Disk Image* free to Australian law enforcement.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] These tools allowed examiners to create an exact copy of a piece of digital media to work on, leaving the original disk intact for verification.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] By the end of the 1990s, as demand for digital evidence grew, more advanced commercial tools such as EnCase and FTK were developed, allowing analysts to examine copies of media without using any live forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] More recently, a trend towards "live memory forensics" has grown, resulting in the availability of tools such as WindowsSCOPE.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] More recently, the same progression of tool development has occurred for mobile devices; initially investigators accessed data directly on the device, but soon specialist tools such as XRY or Radio Tactics Aceso appeared.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Police forces have begun implementing risk-based triage systems to manage the overwhelming demand for digital forensic services.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Acquisition does not normally involve capturing an image of the computer's volatile memory (RAM) unless this is done as part of an incident response investigation.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Typically the task involves creating an exact sector level duplicate (or "forensic duplicate") of the media, often using a write blocking device to prevent modification of the original.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] However, the growth in size of storage media and developments such as cloud computing have led to more use of 'live' acquisitions whereby a 'logical' copy of the data is acquired rather than a complete image of the physical storage device.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Both acquired image (or logical copy) and original media/data are hashed (using an algorithm such as SHA-1 or MD5) and the values compared to verify the copy is accurate.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] An alternative (and patented) approach (that has been dubbed 'hybrid forensics' or 'distributed forensics') combines digital forensics and ediscovery processes.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This approach has been embodied in a commercial tool called ISEEK that was presented together with test results at a conference in 2017.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] During the analysis phase an investigator recovers evidence material using a number of different methodologies and tools.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The evidence recovered is analyzed to reconstruct events or actions and to reach conclusions, work that can often be performed by less specialized staff.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] When an investigation is complete the data is presented, usually in the form of a written report, in lay persons' terms.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Digital forensics is commonly used in both criminal law and private investigation.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Traditionally it has been associated with criminal law, where evidence is collected to support or oppose a hypothesis before the courts.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] As with other areas of forensics this is often a part of a wider investigation spanning a number of disciplines.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In some cases, the collected evidence is used as a form of intelligence gathering, used for other purposes than court proceedings (for example to locate, identify or halt other crimes).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] As a result, intelligence gathering is sometimes held to a less strict forensic standard.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In civil litigation or corporate matters, digital forensics forms part of the electronic discovery (or eDiscovery) process.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Forensic procedures are similar to those used in criminal investigations, often with different legal requirements and limitations.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Outside of the courts digital forensics can form a part of internal corporate investigations.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] A common example might be following unauthorized network intrusion.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] A specialist forensic examination, into the nature and extent of the attack, is performed as a damage limitation exercise, both to establish the extent of any intrusion and in an attempt to identify the attacker.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Such attacks were commonly conducted over phone lines during the 1980s, but in the modern era are usually propagated over the Internet.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The main focus of digital forensics investigations is to recover objective evidence of a criminal activity (termed actus reus in legal parlance).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] However, the diverse range of data held in digital devices can help with other areas of inquiry.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Meta data and other logs can be used to attribute actions to an individual.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] For example, personal documents on a computer drive might identify its owner.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Information provided by those involved can be cross checked with digital evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] the offender's alibi was disproved when mobile phone records of the person he claimed to be with showed she was out of town at the time.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] embedded a Global Unique Identifier into files which identified the computer it had been created on.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Proving whether a file was produced on the digital device being examined or obtained from elsewhere (e.g., the Internet) can be very important.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Related to "Evaluation of source," meta data associated with digital documents can be easily modified (for example, by changing the computer clock you can affect the creation date of a file).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Document authentication relates to detecting and identifying falsification of such details.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] One major limitation to a forensic investigation is the use of encryption; this disrupts initial examination where pertinent evidence might be located using keywords.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Laws to compel individuals to disclose encryption keys are still relatively new and controversial.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] But always more frequently there are solutions to brute force passwords or bypass encryption, such as in smartphones or PCs where by means of bootloader techniques the content of the device can be first acquired and later forced in order to find the password or encryption key.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Concerns have been raised regarding the scientific validation of digital forensic tools and methodologies, which includes the lack of standardized testing frameworks and reproducibility across investigations.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] It is estimated that about 60% of cases that involve encrypted devices, often go unprocessed because there is no way to access the potential evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The examination of digital media is covered by national and international legislation.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] For civil investigations, in particular, laws may restrict the abilities of analysts to undertake examinations.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Restrictions against network monitoring or reading of personal communications often exist.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] During criminal investigation, national laws restrict how much information can be seized.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] For example, in the United Kingdom seizure of evidence by law enforcement is governed by the PACE act.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] During its existence early in the field, the "International Organization on Computer Evidence" (IOCE) was one agency that worked to establish compatible international standards for the seizure of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In the UK, the same laws covering computer crime can also affect forensic investigators.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The 1990 Computer Misuse Act legislates against unauthorized access to computer material.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This is a particular concern for civil investigators who have more limitations than law enforcement.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] An individual's right to privacy is one area of digital forensics which is still largely undecided by courts.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The US Electronic Communications Privacy Act places limitations on the ability of law enforcement or civil investigators to intercept and access evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The act makes a distinction between stored communication (e.g. email archives) and transmitted communication (such as VOIP).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The latter, being considered more of a privacy invasion, is harder to obtain a warrant for.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The ECPA also affects the ability of companies to investigate the computers and communications of their employees, an aspect that is still under debate as to the extent to which a company can perform such monitoring.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Article 5 of the European Convention on Human Rights asserts similar privacy limitations to the ECPA and limits the processing and sharing of personal data both within the EU and with external countries.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The ability of UK law enforcement to conduct digital forensics investigations is legislated by the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] When used in a court of law, digital evidence falls under the same legal guidelines as other forms of evidence, as courts do not usually require more stringent guidelines.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In the United States, the Federal Rules of Evidence are used to evaluate the admissibility of digital evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The United Kingdom PACE and Civil Evidence acts have similar guidelines and many other countries have their own laws.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] US federal laws restrict seizures to items with only obvious evidential value.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This is acknowledged as not always being possible to establish with digital media prior to an examination.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The ease with which digital media can be modified means that documenting the chain of custody from the crime scene, through analysis and, ultimately, to the court, (a form of audit trail) is important to establish the authenticity of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Attorneys have argued that because digital evidence can theoretically be altered it undermines the reliability of the evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] US judges are beginning to reject this theory, in the case *US v.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Bonallo* the court ruled that "the fact that it is possible to alter data contained in a computer is plainly insufficient to establish untrustworthiness." In the United Kingdom, guidelines such as those issued by ACPO are followed to help document the authenticity and integrity of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Digital investigators, particularly in criminal investigations, have to ensure that conclusions are based upon factual evidence and their own expert knowledge.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The sub-branches of digital forensics may each have their own specific guidelines for the conduct of investigations and the handling of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] For example, mobile phones may be required to be placed in a Faraday shield during seizure or acquisition to prevent further radio traffic to the device.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In the UK forensic examination of computers in criminal matters is subject to ACPO guidelines.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] There are also international approaches to providing guidance on how to handle electronic evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The "Electronic Evidence Guide" by the Council of Europe offers a framework for law enforcement and judicial authorities in countries who seek to set up or enhance their own guidelines for the identification and handling of electronic evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The admissibility of digital evidence relies on the tools used to extract it.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In the US, forensic tools are subjected to the Daubert standard, where the judge is responsible for ensuring that the processes and software used were acceptable.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In a 2003 paper, Brian Carrier argued that the Daubert guidelines required the code of forensic tools to be published and peer-reviewed.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In 2011, Josh Brunty stated that the scientific validation of the technology and software associated with performing a digital forensic examination is critical to any laboratory process.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] One of the key issues relating to validating forensic tools is determining a 'baseline' or reference point for tool testing/evaluation.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] There have been numerous attempts to provide an environment for testing the functionality of forensic tools such as the Computer Forensic Tool Testing (CFTT) programme developed by NIST ".
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] To allow for the different environments in which practitioners operate there have also been many attempts to create a framework for customizing test/evaluation environments.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] These resources focus on a single or limited number of target systems.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] However, they do not scale well when attempts are made to test/evaluate tools designed for large networks or the cloud which have become more commonplace in investigations over the years.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Digital forensics investigation is not restricted to retrieve data merely from the computer, as laws are breached by the criminals and small digital devices (e.g. tablets, smartphones, flash drives) are now extensively used.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Some of these devices have volatile memory while some have non-volatile memory.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Sufficient methodologies are available to retrieve data from volatile memory, however, there is lack of detailed methodology or a framework for data retrieval from non-volatile memory sources.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Depending on the type of devices, media or artifacts, digital forensics investigation is branched into various types.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The goal of computer forensics is to explain the current state of a digital artifact; such as a computer system, storage medium or electronic document.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] The discipline usually covers computers, embedded systems (digital devices with rudimentary computing power and onboard memory) and static memory (such as USB pen drives).
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Computer forensics can deal with a broad range of information; from logs (such as internet history) through to the actual files on the drive.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In 2007, prosecutors used a spreadsheet recovered from the computer of Joseph Edward Duncan to show premeditation and secure the death penalty.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Sharon Lopatka's killer was identified in 2006 after email messages from him detailing torture and death fantasies were found on her computer.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Mobile device forensics is a sub-branch of digital forensics relating to recovery of digital evidence or data from a mobile device.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] It differs from Computer forensics in that a mobile device will have an inbuilt communication system (e.g.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] GSM) and, usually, proprietary storage mechanisms.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Investigations usually focus on simple data such as call data and communications (SMS/Email) rather than in-depth recovery of deleted data.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] SMS data from a mobile device investigation helped to exonerate Patrick Lumumba in the murder of Meredith Kercher.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Mobile devices are also useful for providing location information; either from inbuilt GPS/location tracking or via cell site logs, which track the devices within their range.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Such information was used to track down the kidnappers of Thomas Onofri in 2006.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Network forensics is concerned with the monitoring and analysis of computer network traffic, both local and WAN/internet, for the purposes of information gathering, evidence collection, or intrusion detection.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Traffic is usually intercepted at the packet level, and either stored for later analysis or filtered in real-time.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Unlike other areas of digital forensics network data is often volatile and rarely logged, making the discipline often reactionary.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] In 2000, the FBI lured computer hackers Aleksey Ivanov and Gorshkov to the United States for a fake job interview.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] By monitoring network traffic from the pair's computers, the FBI identified passwords allowing them to collect evidence directly from Russian-based computers.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Forensic Data Analysis is a branch of digital forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] It examines structured data with the aim to discover and analyze patterns of fraudulent activities resulting from financial crime.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Digital image forensics (or forensic image analysis) is a branch of digital forensics that deals with examination and verification of an image's authenticity and content.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] These can range from Stalin-era airbrushed photos to elaborate deepfake videos.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] This has broad implications for a wide variety of crimes, for determining the validity of information presented in civil and criminal trials, and for verifying images and information that are circulated through news and social media.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Database forensics is a branch of digital forensics relating to the forensic study of databases and their metadata.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] Investigations use database contents, log files and in-RAM data to build a timeline or recover relevant information.
[src:digital-forensics/digital-forensics] IoT forensics is a branch of Digital forensics that has the goal of identifying and extracting digital information from devices belonging to the Internet of things field, to be used for forensics investigations as potential source of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] It is used in IT forensics and data recovery.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Carving is typically used on storage media with a corrupted file system or for storage areas that are listed as free in the existing file system.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] All filesystems contain some metadata that describes the actual file system.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] At a minimum, this includes the hierarchy of folders and files, with names for each.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The filesystem will also record the physical locations on the storage device where each file is stored.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] As explained below, a file might be scattered in fragments at different physical addresses.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] File carving is the process of trying to recover files without this metadata.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] This is done by analyzing the raw data and identifying what it is (text, executable, png, mp3, etc.).
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] This can be done in different ways, but the simplest is to look for the file signature or "magic numbers" that mark the beginning and/or end of a particular file type.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] For instance, every Java class file has as its first four bytes the hexadecimal value `CA FE BA BE`.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Some files contain footers as well, making it just as simple to identify the ending of the file.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Most file systems, such as the FAT family and UNIX's Fast File System, work with the concept of clusters of an equal and fixed size.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] For example, a FAT32 file system might be broken into clusters of 4 KiB each.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Any file smaller than 4 KiB fits into a single cluster, and there is never more than one file in each cluster.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Files that take up more than 4 KiB are allocated across many clusters.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Sometimes these clusters are all contiguous, while other times they are scattered across two or potentially many more so called fragments, with each fragment containing a number of contiguous clusters storing one part of the file's data.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Obviously, large files are more likely to be fragmented.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Simson Garfinkel reported fragmentation statistics collected from over 350 disks containing FAT, NTFS and UFS file systems.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] He showed that while fragmentation in a typical disk is low, the fragmentation rate of forensically important files such as email, JPEG and Word documents is relatively high.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The fragmentation rate of JPEG files was found to be 16%, Word documents had 17% fragmentation, AVI had a 22% fragmentation rate and PST files (Microsoft Outlook) had a 58% fragmentation rate (the fraction of files being fragmented into two or more fragments).
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Pal, Shanmugasundaram, and Memon presented an efficient algorithm based on a greedy heuristic and alpha-beta pruning for reassembling fragmented images.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Pal, Sencar, and Memon introduced sequential hypothesis testing as an effective mechanism for detecting fragmentation points.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Richard and Roussev presented Scalpel, an open-source file-carving tool existing since 2005 and initially based on Foremost.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] File carving is a highly complex task, with a potentially huge number of permutations to try.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] To make this task tractable, carving software typically makes extensive use of models and heuristics.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] This is necessary not only from a standpoint of execution time, but also for the accuracy of the results.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] State-of-the-art file carving algorithms use statistical techniques like sequential hypothesis testing for determining fragmentation points.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] In most cases, when a file is deleted, the entry in the file system metadata is removed but the actual data is still on the disk.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] File carving can be used to recover data from a hard disk where the metadata was removed or otherwise damaged.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] This process may be successful even after a drive is formatted or repartitioned.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] File carving can be performed using free or commercial software and is often performed in conjunction with computer forensics examinations or alongside other recovery efforts (e.g. hardware repair) by data recovery companies.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Whereas the primary goal of data recovery is to recover the file content, computer forensics examiners are often just as interested in the metadata such as who owned a file, where it was stored, and when it was last modified.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Thus, while a forensic examiner could use file carving to prove that a file was once stored on a hard drive, he or she might need to seek out other evidence to prove who put it there.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Garfinkel introduced the use of fast object validation for reassembling files that have been split into two pieces.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] This technique is referred to as Bifragment Gap Carving (BGC).
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] A set of starting fragments and a set of finishing fragments are identified.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The fragments are reassembled if together they form a valid object.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Pal developed a carving scheme that is not limited to bifragmented files.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The technique, known as SmartCarving, makes use of heuristics regarding the fragmentation behavior of known filesystems.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The algorithm has three phases: preprocessing, collation, and reassembly.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] In the preprocessing phase, blocks are decompressed and/or decrypted if necessary.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] In the collation phase, blocks are sorted according to their file type.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] In the reassembly phase, the blocks are placed in sequence to reproduce the deleted files.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The SmartCarving algorithm is the basis for the Adroit Photo Forensics and Adroit Photo Recovery applications from Digital Assembly.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Snapshots of computers' volatile memory (i.e.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Memory-dump carving is routinely used in digital forensics, allowing investigators to access ephemeral evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] Ephemeral evidence includes recently accessed images and Web pages, documents, chats and communications committed via social networks.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] For example, LiME can be used in conjunction with Volatility to do such a task.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] If an encrypted volume (TrueCrypt, BitLocker, PGP Disk) was used, binary keys to encrypted containers can be extracted and used to instantly mount such volumes.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] The content of volatile memory gets fragmented.
[src:digital-forensics/file-carving] A proprietary carving algorithm was developed by Belkasoft to enable carving fragmented memory sets (BelkaCarving).
[src:digital-forensics/indicator-of-compromise] An **indicator of compromise** (**IoC**) in computer forensics is an artifact observed on a computer network or within an operating system that, with high confidence, indicates a computer intrusion.
[src:digital-forensics/indicator-of-compromise] Common IoCs include virus signatures, suspicious IP addresses, MD5 hashes of malware files, and malicious URLs or domain names associated with botnet command-and-control servers.
[src:digital-forensics/indicator-of-compromise] Once IoCs are identified through incident response or forensic analysis, they can be used for early detection of future attacks with intrusion detection systems and antivirus software.
[src:digital-forensics/indicator-of-compromise] Known indicators are often exchanged within the cybersecurity industry, commonly using the Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) to indicate how information may be shared.
[src:digital-forensics/indicator-of-compromise] Other frameworks and standards are also used to support secure information sharing.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Until the early 2000s, memory forensics was done on an ad hoc basis (termed *unstructured analysis*), often using generic data analysis tools like strings and grep.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] These tools are not specifically created for memory forensics, and therefore are difficult to use.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] In general, their primary usage is to extract text from the memory dump.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Many operating systems provide features to kernel developers and end-users to actually create a snapshot of the physical memory for either debugging (e.g. core dump or Blue Screen of Death) purposes or experience enhancement (e.g. hibernation).
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] In the case of Microsoft Windows, crash dumps and hibernation had been present since Microsoft Windows NT.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Microsoft crash dumps had always been analyzable by Microsoft WinDbg, and Windows hibernation files (hiberfil.sys) are nowadays convertible in Microsoft crash dumps using utilities like MoonSols Windows Memory Toolkit designed by Matthieu Suiche.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] One significant step towards *structured analysis* was in a February 2004 article in SysAdmin Magazine, where Michael Ford demonstrated a more rigorous practice of memory forensics.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] In that article, he analyzes a memory based rootkit utilizing the existing Linux crash utility as well as two tools developed specifically to recover and analyze the memory forensically, memget and mempeek.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] In 2005, DFRWS issued a Memory Analysis Forensics Challenge.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] In response to this challenge, more tools in this generation, specifically designed to analyze memory dumps, were created - such as MoonSols, KntTools, the FATKit, VolaTools, and Volatility.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] These tools had knowledge of the operating system's internal data structures, and were thus capable of reconstructing the operating system's process list and process information.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Although intended as research tools, they proved that operating system level memory forensics is possible and practical.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Subsequently, several memory forensics tools were developed intended for practical use.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] These include both commercial tools like Responder PRO, Memoryze, winen, Belkasoft Live RAM Capturer, etc..
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] New features have been added, such as analysis of Linux and Mac OS X memory dumps, and substantial academic research has been carried out.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Unlike Microsoft Windows, Mac OS X interest is relatively new and had only been initiated by Matthieu Suiche in 2010 during Black Hat Briefings security conference.
[src:digital-forensics/memory-forensics] Currently, memory forensics is a standard component of incident response.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] A **forensic disk controller** or **hardware write-block device** is a specialized type of computer hard disk controller made for the purpose of gaining read-only access to computer hard drives without the risk of damaging the drive's contents.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] The device is named forensic because its most common application is for use in investigations where a computer hard drive may contain evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Such a controller historically has been made in the form of a dongle that fits between a computer and an IDE or SCSI hard drive, but with the advent of USB and SATA, forensic disk controllers supporting these newer technologies have become widespread.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Steve Bress and Mark Menz invented hard drive write blocking (US Patent 6,813,682).
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] A device which is installed between a storage media under investigation and an investigator's computer is called a "**bridge kit**".
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] The bridge kit has one connector for the storage media and another connector the investigator's computer.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] It allows the investigator to read, but not alter the device under investigation.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Forensic disk controllers intercept write commands from the host operating system, preventing them from reaching the drive.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Whenever the host bus architecture supports it the controller reports that the drive is read-only.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] The disk controller can either deny all writes to the disk and report them as failures, or use on-board memory to cache the writes for the duration of the session.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] A disk controller that caches writes in memory presents the appearance to the operating system that the drive is writable, and uses the memory to ensure that the operating system sees changes to the individual disk sectors it attempted to overwrite.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] It does this by retrieving sectors from the disk if the operating system hasn't attempted to change them, and retrieving the changed version from memory for sectors that have been changed.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Forensic disk controllers are most commonly associated with the process of creating a disk image, or acquisition, during forensic analysis.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Their use is to prevent inadvertent modification of evidence.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Using hardware to protect the hard drive from writes is very important for several reasons.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] First, many operating systems, including Windows, may write to any hard disk that is connected to the system.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] At the very least, Windows will update the access time for any file accessed, and may write things to the disk unexpectedly - such as creating hidden folders for the recycle bin or saved hardware configuration.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Virus infections or malware on the system used for analysis may attempt to infect the disk being inspected.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Additionally, the NTFS file system may attempt to commit or rollback unfinished transactions, and/or change flags on the volume to mark it as "in use".
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] At the worst, undesired files may allocate and overwrite deleted space on the hard disk which may potentially destroy evidence in the form of previously deleted files.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Protecting an evidence drive from writes during investigation is also important to counter potential allegations that the contents of the drive were altered during the investigation.
[src:digital-forensics/write-blocker] Of course, this can be alleged anyway, but in the absence of technology to protect a drive from writes, there is no way for such an allegation to be refuted.
